# CHRONOS — Cursor Rules
# Plataforma Inteligente de Gestão de Relógios de Luxo
# Client: Marcelo Miranda Soares Neto
# Build: Horizon

## PROJECT IDENTITY
- Name: Chronos
- Stack: Next.js 14+ (App Router), TypeScript strict, Supabase (Postgres + Auth + Storage + RLS), Tailwind CSS, Shadcn/UI
- External APIs: Evolution API (WhatsApp), Nano Banana Pro 2 via fal.ai (image generation), Gemini Vision (image analysis)
- Architecture: Clean Architecture + SOLID + OOP
- Language: Brazilian Portuguese for UI text, English for code (variable names, comments, types)

## ARCHITECTURE RULES (MANDATORY)

### Layer Structure
```
src/
  app/                    # Next.js routes, layouts, route handlers, server actions
  domain/                 # Entities, value objects, domain services, ports (interfaces)
  application/            # Use cases (commands & queries)
  infrastructure/         # Supabase, Storage, NanoBanana, EvolutionAPI, Vision adapters
  shared/                 # Errors, result types, Zod schemas, constants
```

### Layer Dependencies (STRICT)
- `domain/` → ZERO external imports. No Next.js, no Supabase, no React. Pure TypeScript only.
- `application/` → imports from `domain/` only. Never from `infrastructure/` or `app/`.
- `infrastructure/` → imports from `domain/` (implements ports). Never from `application/` or `app/`.
- `app/` → imports from `application/` and `shared/`. Uses `infrastructure/` only via composition root (`src/lib/di.ts`).
- `shared/` → ZERO imports from other project layers. Only external libs (Zod, etc).

### Dependency Injection
- All use cases receive dependencies via constructor injection (ports/interfaces).
- Composition root at `src/lib/di.ts` wires real implementations.
- NEVER instantiate infrastructure classes directly inside use cases or route handlers.
```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT
const useCase = container.resolve(CreateWatchUseCase);
// or
const useCase = new CreateWatchUseCase(
  new SupabaseWatchRepository(supabase),
  new SupabaseImageStorage(supabase),
);

// ❌ WRONG
const supabase = createClient();
const { data } = await supabase.from('watches').insert(...); // direct DB in route handler
```

### Entities & Value Objects
- Entities have identity (id), encapsulate invariants, validate on construction.
- Value objects are immutable, compared by value.
- NEVER use raw objects/records from Supabase as domain entities. Always map at the infrastructure boundary.
```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT
export class Watch {
  private constructor(private readonly props: WatchProps) {
    this.validate();
  }
  static create(input: CreateWatchInput): Watch { ... }
  static fromPersistence(raw: WatchRow): Watch { ... }
  toPersistence(): WatchRow { ... }
}

// ❌ WRONG
type Watch = Database['public']['Tables']['watches']['Row'];
```

### Use Cases
- One file per use case. Name pattern: `VerbNounUseCase.ts` (e.g., `CreateWatchUseCase.ts`).
- Each use case has a single public `execute()` method.
- Returns `Result<T, E>` pattern, never throws for expected errors.
```typescript
export class CreateWatchUseCase {
  constructor(
    private readonly watchRepo: IWatchRepository,
    private readonly imageStorage: IImageStorage,
  ) {}
  async execute(input: CreateWatchInput): Promise<Result<Watch, CreateWatchError>> { ... }
}
```

### Ports (Interfaces)
- All external dependencies are abstracted as interfaces in `domain/ports/`.
- Naming: `I{Name}` prefix for interfaces.
```typescript
// domain/ports/IWatchRepository.ts
export interface IWatchRepository {
  findById(id: string): Promise<Watch | null>;
  save(watch: Watch): Promise<void>;
  findByFilters(filters: WatchFilters): Promise<PaginatedResult<Watch>>;
}

// domain/ports/IMessageDispatcher.ts
export interface IMessageDispatcher {
  sendMedia(params: SendMediaParams): Promise<Result<void, DispatchError>>;
  sendText(params: SendTextParams): Promise<Result<void, DispatchError>>;
}

// domain/ports/IMarketingAssetGenerator.ts
export interface IMarketingAssetGenerator {
  generateCard(params: GenerateCardParams): Promise<Result<GeneratedAsset, GenerationError>>;
}

// domain/ports/IImageAnalyzer.ts
export interface IImageAnalyzer {
  analyzeWatch(imageUrl: string): Promise<Result<WatchSuggestions, AnalysisError>>;
}
```

## SUPABASE RULES

### Client Usage
- NEVER use `supabase` client directly in `app/` route handlers or server actions.
- All Supabase calls go through repository/adapter classes in `infrastructure/`.
- Use `createServerClient` for server-side (route handlers, server actions, server components).
- Use `createBrowserClient` ONLY in client components that need realtime subscriptions.
- NEVER expose `service_role` key to the browser.

### Row Level Security
- EVERY table MUST have RLS enabled.
- ALL policies use `auth.uid()` joined through `memberships` table to verify org access.
- NEVER use `security definer` functions unless absolutely necessary (document why).
- Test RLS policies: always verify a user cannot access another org's data.

### Storage
- Buckets: `watch-images`, `finance-attachments`, `marketing-assets`.
- Policies mirror table RLS via org membership.
- Always generate signed URLs for private content; public bucket only for storefront images.

### Migrations
- SQL migration files in `supabase/migrations/` with timestamp prefix.
- Each migration is idempotent where possible (use `IF NOT EXISTS`).
- NEVER modify a migration after it has been applied. Create a new migration instead.

## NEXT.JS RULES

### Route Handlers (API)
- Thin adapters: parse request → call use case → format response.
- Validate input with Zod at the edge.
- NEVER put business logic in route handlers.
```typescript
// app/api/v1/watches/route.ts
export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const body = await req.json();
  const parsed = CreateWatchSchema.safeParse(body);
  if (!parsed.success) return NextResponse.json({ error: parsed.error }, { status: 400 });

  const useCase = container.resolve(CreateWatchUseCase);
  const result = await useCase.execute(parsed.data);

  if (result.isErr()) return NextResponse.json({ error: result.error }, { status: 422 });
  return NextResponse.json(result.value, { status: 201 });
}
```

### Server Actions
- Use for form mutations tightly coupled to UI when it reduces boilerplate.
- Still call use cases behind the scenes (same as route handlers).
- Validate with Zod before calling use case.

### Server Components
- Default for all pages. Use `"use client"` only when interactivity requires it.
- Fetch data via use cases (query use cases), not direct Supabase calls.

### Client Components
- Minimize. Only for: forms with complex state, realtime subscriptions, interactive UI (drag-drop, modals).
- Prefix with `"use client"` directive.

## TYPESCRIPT RULES
- `strict: true` in tsconfig. No `any` except in test mocks with explicit cast.
- Use `unknown` instead of `any` for untyped external data, then validate with Zod.
- Prefer `type` over `interface` for DTOs; use `interface` for ports/contracts.
- Enums: use `as const` objects instead of TypeScript `enum`.
```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT
export const WATCH_STATUS = {
  DRAFT: 'draft',
  AVAILABLE: 'available',
  RESERVED: 'reserved',
  SOLD: 'sold',
  CONSIGNED: 'consigned',
} as const;
export type WatchStatus = typeof WATCH_STATUS[keyof typeof WATCH_STATUS];

// ❌ WRONG
enum WatchStatus { Draft, Available, Reserved, Sold }
```

## UI / STYLING RULES
- Tailwind CSS + Shadcn/UI components. No custom CSS files unless strictly necessary.
- Dark theme as default (luxury aesthetic). Color tokens defined in `tailwind.config.ts`.
- Color palette: navy (`#0F1724`), gold (`#C9A84C`), dark surface (`#12121A`), muted text (`#7A7A8A`).
- All UI text in Brazilian Portuguese.
- Responsive: mobile-first, but primary UX is desktop (Marcelo uses desktop mostly).
- Loading states: skeleton components, never blank screens.
- Error states: toast notifications via Sonner, not alert() or console.log.

## NAMING CONVENTIONS
- Files: `kebab-case.ts` for all files. Exception: React components in `PascalCase.tsx`.
- Database: `snake_case` for tables, columns, and functions.
- TypeScript: `camelCase` for variables/functions, `PascalCase` for types/classes/interfaces.
- Use cases: `VerbNounUseCase` (e.g., `CreateWatchUseCase`, `ListClientsUseCase`).
- Repositories: `Supabase{Entity}Repository` (e.g., `SupabaseWatchRepository`).
- Adapters: `{Provider}{Capability}Adapter` (e.g., `EvolutionWhatsAppAdapter`, `NanoBananaImageAdapter`).

## ERROR HANDLING
- Domain errors are typed classes extending a base `DomainError`.
- Use Result pattern (`Result<T, E>`) for expected errors. Never throw for business rule violations.
- Throw only for unexpected/programmer errors (bugs).
- Route handlers catch and map errors to HTTP status codes.
- Log all errors with structured context (userId, watchId, action).

## SECURITY CHECKLIST (EVERY PR)
- [ ] No `service_role` key in client-side code.
- [ ] RLS enabled on any new table.
- [ ] Input validated with Zod before use case execution.
- [ ] No raw SQL interpolation (use parameterized queries).
- [ ] Auth checked in route handler/middleware before use case.
- [ ] Financial amounts stored as integer cents (never float).
- [ ] Sensitive fields (price, cost) only visible to authorized roles.

## GIT / WORKFLOW
- Branch naming: `phase-{N}/task-{NN}-{short-description}` (e.g., `phase-1/task-03-watch-crud`).
- Commit messages: conventional commits (`feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, `chore:`).
- One task per PR. Small, reviewable PRs.

## WHAT NOT TO DO
- NEVER put business logic in React components.
- NEVER call Supabase directly from app/ layer (always through infrastructure).
- NEVER use `any` type without explicit justification.
- NEVER store money as float. Use integer cents.
- NEVER skip Zod validation at API boundaries.
- NEVER create a migration that drops data without explicit confirmation.
- NEVER hardcode API keys. Use environment variables.
- NEVER commit .env files.
- NEVER use `console.log` in production code. Use structured logger.
- NEVER skip RLS on any table.
